Common pitfalls to carry forward.

Not in with a null in the list returns zero rows, so either guarantee no nulls or rewrite with not exists. Like with a leading percent sign cannot use a standard b-tree index and forces a full scan; reach for trigram indexes or full-text search there. And between is inclusive on both ends, so for half-open ranges over timestamps, like all of April, prefer greater or equal to the first of April and less than the first of May.

Null ordering defaults differ across dialects, so write nulls first or nulls last explicitly whenever correctness depends on it. And limit without order by gives non-deterministic results; add the order even in throwaway queries, because habits stick.

Finally, two more. Don't reach for union when union all is correct, because union does an implicit dedup that costs a sort or a hash table. And don't mix and with or without parentheses, because and binds tighter, so a, or b and c, means a, or the quantity b and c.
